column13: Fixed erroneous post-send assertion on the amount of data sent.
column20:
The assertion fails if the amount of bytes sent is equal to the payload size. This is wrong because as per the java doc on the org.apache.qpid.proton.engine.Sender.send method, these two values will always be equal when successful.
This problem is not usually visible because java assert keyword is not intended for production code and is disabled by default. However, test runners typically enable it by passing the -ea flag to the jvm. In my case it was causing the tests to fail.
I’ve also debugged it against the sample code provided with the SDK. Since it uses the static main method the IDE runners do not pass the -ea flag and the assertion is not enabled. However, if it were enabled, the send would fail on it despite being successful, i.e., event being successfully written to the event hub.
I suggest releasing this fix under 0.6.5 version.

column20:
Impact: allows to control send latency.
Remaining Work: expose the configuration to end clients. Currently using defaults, based on empirical trials
Context:
I've noticed that EventHubClient.send(...).get() takes at least 3100ms and is very consistent around this value.
I've established this using a simple send-receive manual test, whereby I was running
the example code for sending and receiving in the loop and reporting send times to the console. While not very scientific it was reliably reproducible and consistent
with latency regression observed after migration to this SDK.


I observed that end-to-end latency is very similar to the posting latency. I've also knew that Event Hubs themselves can easily achieve much better latencies.
Ergo, the problem must occur during send.


With help of jvisualvm I've ruled out contention/locking issues


By tapping into the complete call on the CompletableFuture returned by the send operation, I've established that the reactor is responsible for dispatching completion
events.


Finally, looking at how it is initialized, I've discovered that the ReactorImpl.run() method sets the timeout to 3141 which is suspiciously close to the send latency
I've been observing.


Taking down this timeout to 100ms took down the posting latency to < 300ms, when run from my laptop in Europe to a DC in East US.

column13: Allow EventHub path to be specified when using IoT Hub connection string
column20:
Currently, the path for an event hub when using an IoT Hub connection string is hardcoded to messages/events/. However, there are multiple different valid paths when using an IoT Hub (messages/operationsMonitoringEvents/, messages/deviceBound, etc.).
This change allows the user to provide their own path when using an IoT Hub, defaulting to messages/events/ when none is provided.

Also: refactor Azure Storage lease manager to centralize lease update.

Also: refactor Azure Storage lease manager to centralize lease update.

What about overriding the entity path param, with the entity path in the connection string? I did commit a change with that, and a comment describing the behavior. If you think it is better to throw, I can easily do that too.
We may need to adjust the EPH constructor as well to allow the absence of the Entity Path (assuming it is in the connection string). If we have it in both, it will probably be confusing. I.E. column20: Added optional entity name param to EventHubsConnectionSettings constructor so that you can allow the EPH to pass a connection string without the entitypath. Using the optional param allows you to always pass the param and handle the null check inside the constructor rather than in the calling method.
column21:
eventhHubPath is currently a mandatory argument for all EPH constructors. For addressing EventProcessorHost issue, we can remove eventhHubPath and expect path to be present in the connection string. This will be more aligned with the rest of the the API, such as we expect entity path to be present in the connection string while creating EventHubClient.
On the other hand, .NET client asks for entityPath as a separate argument on the EPH constructors and it doesn't allow connection string to contain entity path. This contract is completely opposite of what I offered above for CoreCLR but at least it is deterministic. Let us discuss this in person.

column20: In this PR, we reduce the scope of this repo to simply enumerate the existing ecosystem and provide links to get there.
column21:
Hey @jackbond, we talked about it and this didn't seem like a good place for anything besides encapsulating our open-source ecosystem and providing samples. Issues were being opened and not being tracked which I really hate to see. For any type of issue, there is a better channel to report it than this one:

Documentation issues/feedback -> File an issue here https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs
Library issues/feedback -> File an issue in the respective repo
Service-side issues -> Open a support ticket on Azure (which comes straight to our team!)
Service-side feedback/requests -> I'm in the process of getting something like this setup for Event Hubs

Once we have the feedback forum setup, adding the correct support/feedback channels to the README on this repo may be a good idea.
Now, with all that said, our goal was not to make this repo seem "gutted". Is there anything that you feel is missing now that you appreciated? Is there anything else you think this repo should provide? We'd love feedback on this and we're willing to implement good ideas as they come in 👍
Thank you for taking the time!
P.S. This is not an Azure-wide initiative - this is just us (the Event Hubs team) trying to make sure we have a good process in place!

column20: In this PR, we reduce the scope of this repo to simply enumerate the existing ecosystem and provide links to get there.
column21: @sabeegrewal Ok, so the other EventHub GitHubs like https://github.com/azure/azure-event-hubs-dotnet will remain unchanged?

column20: In this PR, we reduce the scope of this repo to simply enumerate the existing ecosystem and provide links to get there.
column21:
Yes! Users that use our open-source stuff should be able to get support fast via GitHub - that's the goal we're seriously pushing for. We're happy to (and want to) support our GitHub projects on GitHub :)
cc @sjkwak

There are compile errors in the java examples:

the artifact+groupId of the advancedsendoptions was set to "simplesend" (i guess copy pasta error). this breaks the maven build as submodule names are unique.
code of some examples has not been updated when the dependency for azure-eventhubs was upgraded from 0.15.1 to >1.0.0. This version bump includes breaking API changes, hence it doesn't compile anymore.

This PR addresses these issues.

column21: I notice that this is bound to Preview 6.   I wanted to mention that there's been some hierarchy cleanup that will appear in the next release, where types have been organized into namespaces based on their primary operation.   For example, types related to reading events will appear in the Azure.Messaging.EventHubs.Consumer namespace and, likewise, types responsible for publishing events in the Azure.Messaging.EventHubs.Producer namespace.    Outside of adjusting the namespaces, I don't see anything that I believe would break if shifting form preview 6 to the next release. #Resolved

The DWDumper project lists the older Key Vault package in the csproj file, but does not use it anywhere in code
The DWDumper project also uses the older Storage package. It should use Azure.Storage.Blobs instead

l have updated these file, and use new package Azure.Storage.Blobs in DWDumper project.
@ramya-rao-a , @jongio for notification.

column20:
Bumps Apache.Avro from 1.7.7.2 to 1.11.0.

Release notes
Sourced from Apache.Avro's releases.

Apache Avro 1.11.0
The Apache Avro community is pleased to announce the release of Avro 1.11.0!
All signed release artifacts, signatures and verification instructions can
be found here: https://avro.apache.org/releases.html
This release includes 120 Jira issues, including some interesting features:
Specification: AVRO-3212 Support documentation tags for FIXED types
C#: AVRO-2961 Support dotnet framework 5.0
C#: AVRO-3225 Prevent memory errors when deserializing untrusted data
C++: AVRO-2923 Logical type corrections
Java: AVRO-2863 Support Avro core on android
Javascript: AVRO-3131 Drop support for node.js 10
Perl: AVRO-3190 Fix error when reading from EOF
Python: AVRO-2906 Improved performance validating deep record data
Python: AVRO-2914 Drop Python 2 support
Python: AVRO-3004 Drop Python 3.5 support
Ruby: AVRO-3108 Drop Ruby 2.5 support
For the first time, the 1.11.0 release includes experimental support for
Rust.  Work is continuing on this donated SDK, but we have not versioned and
published official artifacts for this release.
Python: The avro package fully supports Python 3. We will no longer publish a
separate avro-python3 package
And of course upgraded dependencies to latest versions, CVE fixes and more:
https://issues.apache.org/jira/issues/?jql=project%3DAVRO%20AND%20fixVersion%3D1.11.0
The link to all fixed JIRA issues and a brief summary can be found at:
https://github.com/apache/avro/releases/tag/release-1.11.0
In addition, language-specific release artifacts are available:

C#: https://www.nuget.org/packages/Apache.Avro/1.11.0
Java: from Maven Central,
Javascript: https://www.npmjs.com/package/avro-js/v/1.11.0
Perl: https://metacpan.org/release/Avro
Python 3: https://pypi.org/project/avro/1.11.0
Ruby: https://rubygems.org/gems/avro/versions/1.11.0

Thanks to everyone for contributing!
Apache Avro 1.10.2
The Apache Avro community is pleased to announce the release of Avro 1.10.2!
All signed release artifacts, signatures and verification instructions can
be found here: https://avro.apache.org/releases.html

column20:
Bumps Apache.Avro from 1.9.2 to 1.11.0.

Release notes
Sourced from Apache.Avro's releases.

Apache Avro 1.11.0
The Apache Avro community is pleased to announce the release of Avro 1.11.0!
All signed release artifacts, signatures and verification instructions can
be found here: https://avro.apache.org/releases.html
This release includes 120 Jira issues, including some interesting features:
Specification: AVRO-3212 Support documentation tags for FIXED types
C#: AVRO-2961 Support dotnet framework 5.0
C#: AVRO-3225 Prevent memory errors when deserializing untrusted data
C++: AVRO-2923 Logical type corrections
Java: AVRO-2863 Support Avro core on android
Javascript: AVRO-3131 Drop support for node.js 10
Perl: AVRO-3190 Fix error when reading from EOF
Python: AVRO-2906 Improved performance validating deep record data
Python: AVRO-2914 Drop Python 2 support
Python: AVRO-3004 Drop Python 3.5 support
Ruby: AVRO-3108 Drop Ruby 2.5 support
For the first time, the 1.11.0 release includes experimental support for
Rust.  Work is continuing on this donated SDK, but we have not versioned and
published official artifacts for this release.
Python: The avro package fully supports Python 3. We will no longer publish a
separate avro-python3 package
And of course upgraded dependencies to latest versions, CVE fixes and more:
https://issues.apache.org/jira/issues/?jql=project%3DAVRO%20AND%20fixVersion%3D1.11.0
The link to all fixed JIRA issues and a brief summary can be found at:
https://github.com/apache/avro/releases/tag/release-1.11.0
In addition, language-specific release artifacts are available:

C#: https://www.nuget.org/packages/Apache.Avro/1.11.0
Java: from Maven Central,

Perl: https://metacpan.org/release/Avro

column20:
Updated the sample used by the tutorial:
https://review.docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/event-hubs/store-captured-data-data-warehouse?branch=pr-en-us-197006

Upgraded the Azure function project FunctionEGDWDumper. Now, the first parameter for the function is of type EventGridEvent and the second parameter is of type ILogger.
Updated the code after updating the two parameters.
Now, the code uses StorageSharedKeyCredentials that's built using the storage account name and the storage access key. Earlier, I had to set the access level for the container to "public" to get the tutorial working.
Updated the template JSON file to set the new configuration values for storage account name and storage account key.
Removed unnecessary DWDumper from the folder and the solution.
Cleaned up Readme.md file to point to the tutorial article on DOCS. This would eliminate duplication of the content. Also, removed all the images used by the old Readme file.

column20:
Bumps gson from 2.8.2 to 2.8.9.

Release notes
Sourced from gson's releases.

Gson 2.8.9

Make OSGi bundle's dependency on sun.misc optional (#1993).
Deprecate Gson.excluder() exposing internal Excluder class (#1986).
Prevent Java deserialization of internal classes (#1991).
Improve number strategy implementation (#1987).
Fix LongSerializationPolicy null handling being inconsistent with Gson (#1990).
Support arbitrary Number implementation for Object and Number deserialization (#1290).
Bump proguard-maven-plugin from 2.4.0 to 2.5.1 (#1980).
Don't exclude static local classes (#1969).
Fix RuntimeTypeAdapterFactory depending on internal Streams class (#1959).
Improve Maven build (#1964).
Make dependency on java.sql optional (#1707).

Gson 2.8.8

Fixed issue with recursive types (#1390).
Better behaviour with Java 9+ and Unsafe if there is a security manager (#1712).
EnumTypeAdapter now works better when ProGuard has obfuscated enum fields (#1495).




Changelog
Sourced from gson's changelog.

Version 2.8.9

Make OSGi bundle's dependency on sun.misc optional (#1993).
Deprecate Gson.excluder() exposing internal Excluder class (#1986).
Prevent Java deserialization of internal classes (#1991).
Improve number strategy implementation (#1987).
Fix LongSerializationPolicy null handling being inconsistent with Gson (#1990).
Support arbitrary Number implementation for Object and Number deserialization (#1290).
Bump proguard-maven-plugin from 2.4.0 to 2.5.1 (#1980).
Don't exclude static local classes (#1969).
Fix RuntimeTypeAdapterFactory depending on internal Streams class (#1959).
Improve Maven build (#1964).
Make dependency on java.sql optional (#1707).

Version 2.8.8

Fixed issue with recursive types (#1390).
Better behaviour with Java 9+ and Unsafe if there is a security manager (#1712).
EnumTypeAdapter now works better when ProGuard has obfuscated enum fields (#1495).

Version 2.8.7

Fixed ISO8601UtilsTest failing on systems with UTC+X.
Improved javadoc for JsonStreamParser.
Updated proguard.cfg (#1693).
Fixed IllegalStateException in JsonTreeWriter (#1592).
Added JsonArray.isEmpty() (#1640).
Added new test cases (#1638).
Fixed OSGi metadata generation to work on JavaSE < 9 (#1603).

Version 2.8.6
2019-10-04  GitHub Diff

Added static methods JsonParser.parseString and JsonParser.parseReader and deprecated instance method JsonParser.parse
Java 9 module-info support

Version 2.8.5
2018-05-21  GitHub Diff

Print Gson version while throwing AssertionError and IllegalArgumentException
Moved utils.VersionUtils class to internal.JavaVersion. This is a potential backward incompatible change from 2.8.4
Fixed issue google/gson#1310 by supporting Debian Java 9

Version 2.8.4
2018-05-01  GitHub Diff

Added a new FieldNamingPolicy, LOWER_CASE_WITH_DOTS that mapps JSON name someFieldName to some.field.name
Fixed issue google/gson#1305 by removing compile/runtime dependency on sun.misc.Unsafe

Version 2.8.3
2018-04-27  GitHub Diff

Added a new API, GsonBuilder.newBuilder() that clones the current builder
Preserving DateFormatter behavior on JDK 9
